Data Analysis for Life Expectancy in Different Countries

By: Sumeet

Introduction

Life expectancy at birth indicates the number of years a newborn infant would live if prevailing patterns of mortality at the time of its birth were to stay the same throughout its life. (United Nations Population Division)

About the Dataset

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets

Number of Variables: 18

Number of Countries: 178

Number of Years: 16

Number of Rows : 2849

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

data= pd.read_csv("life_expectancy.csv")

print(data.head())

print(data.describe())

print(data.isnull().sum())

data.fillna(method='ffill', inplace=True)

print(data.isnull().sum())


data.columns = data.columns.str.strip()

life_expectancy_upper_limit = data['Life expectancy'].quantile(0.99)
data.loc[data['Life expectancy'] > life_expectancy_upper_limit, 'Life expectancy'] = life_expectancy_upper_limit

duplicates = data.duplicated().sum()
print('Number of duplicate values = ',duplicates)

# Create a new variable for GDP per capita
data['GDP_per_capita'] = data['GDP'] / data['Population']

Correlation Matrix

The correlation matrix is a visual tool that shows how different variables are related to each other. In this matrix, cells highlighted in red indicate a positive relationship—meaning that as one variable increases, the other tends to increase as well. Cells highlighted in blue represent a negative relationship—where an increase in one variable usually leads to a decrease in the other. The color bar on the right helps you understand the strength of these relationships.

Line Plot

The line plot shows the trend in infant and under-five death rates from 2000 to 2014. It reveals a steady decrease in these death rates over time, indicating improvements in child health during this period.

Scatter Plot

The scatter plot displays the relationship between total healthcare spending and life expectancy. It shows that there is no clear connection between how much is spent on healthcare and the length of life, suggesting that other factors may play a more significant role in determining life expectancy.

top_n = 5  #  top N countries with the highest life expectancy

data_filtered = data[data['Country'].isin(countries_with_top_life_expectancy)]

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='Life expectancy', hue='Country', data=data_filtered)
plt.title(f'Top {top_n} Countries with Highest Life Expectancy Across Different Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Life Expectancy')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Line Chart

The line chart shows that life expectancy has generally been increasing over the years in the five countries with the highest life expectancy. However, it's important to note that there are some ups and downs in the life expectancy values over time, even though the overall trend is upward.

top_n = 5  #  top N countries with the lowest life expectancy
countries_with_top_life_expectancy = data.groupby('Country')['Life expectancy'].min().nsmallest(top_n).index
data_filtered = data[data['Country'].isin(countries_with_top_life_expectancy)]

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='Life expectancy', hue='Country', data=data_filtered)
plt.title(f'Top {top_n} Countries with Lowest Life Expectancy Across Different Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Life Expectancy')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Line Chart

The line chart illustrates a general upward trend in life expectancy from 2000 to 2014. However, there is a noticeable decline between 2008 and 2011 of life expectancy in Haiti. This dip coincides with the devastating 7.0 magnitude earthquake that struck Haiti in 2010, significantly impacting the population's life expectancy during that period. Although this external event is not reflected in the dataset we're analyzing, it had a profound effect on the observed decrease in life expectancy.

plt.ylabel('Life Expectancy')

plt.show()

Scatter Plot

The scatter plot shows the relationship between GDP (the total value of goods and services a country produces) and life expectancy (how long people live). It reveals that as life expectancy approaches about 85 years, GDP tends to rise as well, reaching close to $60,000.

import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the data from the CSV file
world = gpd.read_file("ne_110m_admin_0_countries.zip")

# Merge the data with the shapefile based on country names
merged_data = world.merge(data, left_on='ADMIN', right_on='Country', how='left')

# Plot the map with a larger figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 15))  # Set a reasonable figsize for the map

# Adjust the aspect ratio and aspect mode to make the map larger
ax = plt.gca()
ax.set_aspect('auto')  # Set the aspect ratio to 'auto'
ax.set_adjustable('datalim')  # Set the aspect mode to 'datalim'

# Plot the choropleth map
merged_data.plot(column='Life expectancy', cmap='viridis', legend=True, ax=ax)
plt.title('Life Expectancy Map')

# Set the axis extent
ax.set_xlim([-180, 180])  # Longitude range (-180 to 180)
ax.set_ylim([-60, 90])    # Latitude range (-60 to 90)

plt.show()

Choropleth map

The choropleth map uses colors to show differences in life expectancy across different areas. The color bar on the right side of the map shows a gradient where yellow represents higher life expectancy and violet represents lower life expectancy. As you move from the top of the map to the bottom, you can see how life expectancy decreases.

import statsmodels.api as sm
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# Assuming you have loaded the 'data' DataFrame properly
# Assuming 'actual_life_expectancy' is the actual value you want to compare with

X = data[['Population', 'Hepatitis B', 'Measles', 'Polio', 'Diphtheria', 'HIV/AIDS', 'infant deaths', 'under-five deaths', 'Total expenditure', 'GDP', 'BMI', 'thinness  1-19 years', 'Alcohol', 'Schooling']]
y = data['Life expectancy']

# Add a constant term to the independent variables (required for the regression)
X = sm.add_constant(X)

# Fit the multiple regression model
model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()

# Now, create the new_data DataFrame
new_data = {
    'const': 1,  # Add the constant term
    'Population': 20000000,
    'Hepatitis B': 75,
    'Measles': 1000,
    'Polio': 85,
    'Diphtheria': 85,
    'HIV/AIDS': 0.05,
    'infant deaths': 20,
    'under-five deaths': 40,
    'Total expenditure': 6.5,
    'GDP': 2000,
    'BMI': 25,
    'thinness  1-19 years': 3,
    'Alcohol': 5,
    'Schooling': 12,
}

# Create a DataFrame from the new_data dictionary
new_data_df = pd.DataFrame(new_data, index=[0])  # Assuming it's a single data point

# Make the prediction
predicted_life_expectancy = model.predict(new_data_df)



# Define the actual life expectancy for comparison
actual_life_expectancy = 75.0  

# Create a horizontal bar plot for visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
bars = plt.barh(['Predicted', 'Actual'], [predicted_life_expectancy[0], actual_life_expectancy], color=['blue', 'green'])
plt.xlabel('Life Expectancy')
plt.title('Predicted vs. Actual Life Expectancy')
plt.xlim(0, 100)  # Adjust the x-axis limits if needed

# Add numerical labels above the bars
for bar in bars:
    plt.text(bar.get_width() + 0.5, bar.get_y() + bar.get_height() / 2, f'{bar.get_width():.2f}', va='center', color='black')

plt.legend(['Predicted Life Expectancy', 'Actual Life Expectancy'])
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Horizontal bar plot

# Adding a grid for better readability
ax.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Adding a background color to the plot
ax.set_facecolor('#f2f2f2')

# Adding a title and adjusting font size
plt.title('Life Expectancy Trend in Canada Over the Years', fontsize=18)

# Adding labels and adjusting font size
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Life Expectancy', fontsize=14)

# Adding custom x-axis ticks for better readability
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=12)

# Adding custom y-axis ticks with 5-year intervals

plt.legend(['Life Expectancy'], loc='lower right', fontsize=12)

# Adding a shaded region to highlight a specific period, if applicable
plt.axvspan(2008, 2012, color='gray', alpha=0.3)

# Display the plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Line Chart

The line chart shows that life expectancy in Canada increased steadily until 2008. However, there was a sharp drop in life expectancy from 87 years in 2008 to 81 years in 2009.
